==English==

===Etymology===
Via Old French ''[[epiphanie]]'', Latin ''[[epiphania]]'' from Greek [[ἐπιφάνεια]] "manifestation, striking appearance", [[-εια]] feminine of [[ἐπιφαίνω]] "appear, display" ([[ἐπι-]] + [[φαίνω]] "shine, appear"). English [[Epiphany]] (of Christ) since the 14th century, generic use since the 17th century.

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-epiphany.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|epiphanies}}

# A [[manifestation]] or [[appearance]] of a [[divine]] or [[superhuman]] [[being]].
# An illuminating [[discovery]] often resulting in a personal feeling of elation.
# A complete and thorough understanding of a previously misunderstood or or not understood concept that comes with a sense of awe and wonder.
# Season or time of the Christian church year from the Epiphany feast day to [[Mardi Gras]] ([[Shrove Tuesday]]), the day before [[Ash Wednesday]], the start of [[Lent]] (See [[Epiphany]]).

